Assignment 3:¶

Student name: James/Peng Li

Student ID: 24008144

Introduction¶

In Assginment 4, we acquired data sets from three different resources:¶

  1. Computer excel file
  • Resource: bp Statistical Review of World Energy 2021 | 70th edition
  • Data: Energy Consumption per Capita 2010-2020
  1. Web API
  • Resource: World Bank
  • Data: GDP per Capita, CO2 per Capita, Forest Area, Population 2010-2020
  1. Web-scraped
  • Resource: form on website
  • Data: Happiness Indicator 2010-2020

We extracted them into follow 6 excel files:¶

  • Data1,energy2010to2020: Energy Consumption per Capita 2010-2020,
  • Data2, worldbank_gdp: GDP per Capita 2010-2020
  • Data3,worldbank_CO2: CO2 per Capita 2010-2020
  • Data4,worldbank_forest: Forest Area 2010-2020
  • Data5, worldbank_population: Population 2010-2020
  • Data6, happiness: Hapiness 2010-2020

Read data into DB and inquires for analysis:¶

We read in all the data and populate the tables from the notebook into DB. After that we perform some analysis that extracting data from DB. Lastly, we create at least two DB Views which encapsulated queries from above and test them.

General analysis logic is still the same as assignment 4, but so detailed as in assignment, with some trails based on data from DB:¶

  • The energy efficiency for GDP. This means for same energy consumption unit which country can achieve higher GDP?
  • The energy efficiency for CO2 emission. This means for same energy consumption unit which country can emit less CO2?
  • The compensation of forest for CO2 emission. Based on the CO2 emission, does the country have certain forest area to compensate the CO2 emission?

cursor.execute('DROP TABLE IF EXISTS energy2010to2020')

table = """
            CREATE TABLE energy2010to2020 (

cursor.execute('DROP TABLE IF EXISTS worldbank_gdp')

table = """
           CREATE TABLE worldbank_gdp (
        Country_name VARCHAR(20) NOT NULL,
        Countrycode VARCHAR(5),
        year INTEGER NOT NULL,
        GDP_per_capita FLOAT NOT NULL,
        PRIMARY KEY (Country_name, year),
        FOREIGN KEY (Country_name, year) REFERENCES energy2010to2020(Country_name, year))
            """
cursor.execute(table)

In [411]:
cursor.execute('DROP TABLE IF EXISTS worldbank_CO2')

table = """
           CREATE TABLE worldbank_CO2 (
        Country_name VARCHAR(20) NOT NULL,
        Countrycode VARCHAR(5),
        year INTEGER NOT NULL,
        CO2_per_capita FLOAT NOT NULL,
        PRIMARY KEY (Country_name, year),
        FOREIGN KEY (Country_name, year) REFERENCES energy2010to2020(Country_name, year))
            """
cursor.execute(table)

cursor.execute('DROP TABLE IF EXISTS worldbank_forest')

table = """
           CREATE TABLE worldbank_forest (
        Country_name VARCHAR(20) NOT NULL,
        Countrycode VARCHAR(5) ,
        year INTEGER NOT NULL,
        ForestArea FLOAT NOT NULL,
        PRIMARY KEY (Country_name, year),
        FOREIGN KEY (Country_name, year) REFERENCES worldbank_CO2(Country_name, year))
            """

In [428]:
cursor.execute('DROP TABLE IF EXISTS worldbank_population')

table = """
           CREATE TABLE worldbank_population (
        Country_name VARCHAR(20) NOT NULL,
        Countrycode VARCHAR(5) ,
        year INTEGER NOT NULL,
        Population FLOAT NOT NULL,
        PRIMARY KEY (Country_name, year),
        FOREIGN KEY (Country_name, year) REFERENCES worldbank_forest(Country_name, year))
            """
cursor.execute(table)

In [436]:
cursor.execute('DROP TABLE IF EXISTS happiness')

table = """
           CREATE TABLE happiness (
        Country_name VARCHAR(20) NOT NULL,
        year INTEGER NOT NULL,
        Life_ladder FLOAT NOT NULL,
        PRIMARY KEY (Country_name, year),
        FOREIGN KEY (Country_name, year) REFERENCES worldbank_gdp(Country_name, year))
            """
cursor.execute(table)

    VALUES (?, ?, ?)

- The diagram from schema DB is similar as the original planed chart above.¶

- Because the original data for forest is just the total forest area, not the forest area per capita, so we also input the data population to calculate the forest area per capita.¶

- All the data sets are linked with the same variable "Country_name" and "year" as FOREIGN KEY.¶

4. Analysis the extracted data from DB¶

4.1 Energy Consumption per Capita (2010-2020) of 10 Selected Countries¶

In [443]:
sql_statement = """
                SELECT 
                Country_name, 
                year, 
                Energy_consumption_per_capita
                FROM energy2010to2020
                WHERE Country_name IN ("Australia", "New Zealand", "United States", "Brazil", "Germany", 
                     "Finland", "South Africa", "Israel", "China", "India");
                """
Energy10=pd.read_sql_query(sql_statement, connection)
Energy10
Out[443]:
Country_name year Energy_consumption_per_capita
0 Australia 2010 240.5
1 Australia 2011 243.3
2 Australia 2012 236.5
3 Australia 2013 235.9
4 Australia 2014 234.8
... ... ... ...
105 United States 2016 284.7
106 United States 2017 283.8
107 United States 2018 292.4
108 United States 2019 288.4
109 United States 2020 265.2

110 rows × 3 columns

In [444]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
for country in Energy10['Country_name'].unique():
    country_data = Energy10[Energy10['Country_name'] == country]
    plt.plot(country_data['year'], country_data['Energy_consumption_per_capita'], label=country)
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Energy Consumption per Capita')
plt.title('Energy Consumption per Capita (2010-2020)')
plt.legend(title='Country')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

From above chart, we can find that:¶

  • From 2010 to 2020, for most the countries we can find the relative stable trend.
  • There is an obvious decrease from 2019 to 2020, which was mainly caused by Covid in 2020.
  • United States, Australia, Finland, New Zealand are ranking top 4 as developed countries. Developing countries such like South Africa, China, Bazil, Indian have relative smaller energy consumption per capita.

4.2 Average Energy Consumption per Capita (2010-2020) and Ranking¶

In [445]:
sql_statement = """
                SELECT 
                    Country_name, 
                    ROUND(AVG(Energy_consumption_per_capita), 1) AS AverageEnergyConsumptionPerCapita
                FROM 
                    energy2010to2020
                WHERE 
                    Country_name IN ("Australia", "New Zealand", "United States", "Brazil", "Germany", 
                                     "Finland", "South Africa", "Israel", "China", "India")
                    AND year BETWEEN 2010 AND 2020
                GROUP BY 
                    Country_name
                ORDER BY 
                    AverageEnergyConsumptionPerCapita DESC;
                """

Energy_10 = pd.read_sql_query(sql_statement, connection)
print(Energy_10)

    Country_name  AverageEnergyConsumptionPerCapita
0  United States                              287.8
1      Australia                              234.0
2        Finland                              213.8
3    New Zealand                              189.1
4        Germany                              162.5
5         Israel                              130.1
6   South Africa                               93.6
7          China                               90.0
8         Brazil                               58.4
9          India                               21.7
In [446]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
Energy_10.plot(kind='bar', x='Country_name', y='AverageEnergyConsumptionPerCapita', color='skyblue')
plt.title('Average Energy Consumption Per Capita (2010-2020)')
plt.xlabel('Country')
plt.ylabel('Average Energy Consumption Per Capita')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

<Figure size 1000x600 with 0 Axes>

From above chart on average from 2010 to 2020, we can find that:¶

  • United States, Australia and Finland as developed countries have the highest energy consumption per capita;
  • Indian is relative low from this side. We see big difference there.

4.3 GDP per Capita (2010-2020) of 10 Selected Countries¶

In [447]:
sql_statement = """
                SELECT 
                Country_name, 
                year, 
                GDP_per_capita
                FROM worldbank_gdp
                WHERE Country_name IN ("Australia", "New Zealand", "United States", "Brazil", "Germany", 
                     "Finland", "South Africa", "Israel", "China", "India");
                """
GDP10=pd.read_sql_query(sql_statement, connection)
GDP10

In [448]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
for country in GDP10['Country_name'].unique():
    country_data = GDP10[GDP10['Country_name'] == country]
    plt.plot(country_data['year'], country_data['GDP_per_capita'], label=country)
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('GDP per capita')
plt.title('GDP per capita (2010-2020)')
plt.legend(title='Country')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

From above chart, we can find that:¶

  • Australia, Germany, Finland, New Zealand and Israel have similar trend and have decrease in 2015 and have overall increasing trend.
  • Developing countries such like South Africa, China, Bazil, Indian are relative smaller. China has also relative good increase.
  • United States has very quick increase all the years.

4.4 Average GDP per Capita (2010-2020) and GDP Efficiency based on Eenergy¶

In [449]:
sql_statement = """
                SELECT 
                    Country_name, 
                    ROUND(AVG(GDP_per_capita)/1000, 1) AS AverageGDPperCapita
                FROM 
                    worldbank_gdp
                WHERE 
                    Country_name IN ("Australia", "New Zealand", "United States", "Brazil", "Germany", 
                                     "Finland", "South Africa", "Israel", "China", "India")
                    AND year BETWEEN 2010 AND 2020
                GROUP BY 
                    Country_name
                ORDER BY 
                    AverageGDPperCapita DESC;
                """
GDP_10 = pd.read_sql_query(sql_statement, connection)
print(GDP_10)

5.1 CREATE VIEW NewZealand_happiness¶

In [468]:
%%sql sqlite:///C:/Users/lpxue/datasets/mySQLiteDB.sl3
CREATE VIEW NewZealand_happiness AS
    SELECT Country_name, year, Life_ladder
    FROM (SELECT 
                Country_name, 
                year, 
                Life_ladder
                FROM happiness)
    WHERE Country_name = 'New Zealand';

from sqlalchemy import create_engine
engine = create_engine('sqlite:///C:/Users/lpxue/datasets/mySQLiteDB.sl3')
query = "SELECT year, Life_ladder FROM NewZealand_happiness"
NewZealand_happiness = pd.read_sql(query, engine)
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(NewZealand_happiness['year'], NewZealand_happiness['Life_ladder'], marker='o', linestyle='-', color='b')
plt.title('Life Ladder by Year in New Zealand')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Life Ladder')
plt.grid(True)
plt.xticks(NewZealand_happiness['year'], rotation=45)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

From above Chart, we find that:¶

  • Happiness of New Zealand has overall high level above 7.
  • It had big decrease in 2007, could mainly be casued by financial crisis in 2007-2008.
  • It went up from 2011 until to 2015 and then kept around 7.3 level.

5.2 CREATE VIEW high_happiness_countries_in_2020¶

In [471]:
%%sql sqlite:///C:/Users/lpxue/datasets/mySQLiteDB.sl3
CREATE VIEW high_happiness_countries_in2020 AS
    SELECT Country_name, year, Life_ladder
    FROM (SELECT 
                Country_name, 
                year, 
                Life_ladder
                FROM happiness
                ORDER BY Life_ladder DESC
         )
    WHERE Life_ladder > 7 AND year = 2020;
